1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:04,269
This is OpenPatch from the very beginning, in one uninterrupted browser recording.

2
00:00:04,269 --> 00:00:09,683
OpenPatch lets people repair websites they do not own, then share that repair safely with everyone else.

3
00:00:09,683 --> 00:00:13,124
First, download the extension from the public OpenPatch site.

4
00:00:13,124 --> 00:00:17,750
Unzip it, open Chrome extensions, enable Developer mode, and choose Load unpacked.

5
00:00:17,750 --> 00:00:23,165
This clean demo profile now shows the real OpenPatch version zero point eight extension running.

6
00:00:23,165 --> 00:00:25,294
Now we open the MetroCare directory.

7
00:00:25,294 --> 00:00:30,440
The original website has twelve services, but no search, no filters, and no comparison.

8
00:00:30,440 --> 00:00:34,817
A person has to read every card to find accessible care in their language.

9
00:00:34,817 --> 00:00:37,139
We open the actual extension on this website.

10
00:00:37,139 --> 00:00:42,608
OpenPatch checks the public registry and discovers a community repair made for this exact domain and path.

11
00:00:42,608 --> 00:00:48,594
It verifies the publisher policy, the patch hash, and all eleven live selector targets before offering installation.

12
00:00:48,594 --> 00:00:51,586
One click installs and activates the verified feature.

13
00:00:51,586 --> 00:00:55,299
This is a constrained OpenPatch document, not arbitrary JavaScript.

14
00:00:55,299 --> 00:01:00,341
It may use only declared operations, and it receives access only to the website it repairs.

15
00:01:00,341 --> 00:01:03,706
The page reloads with the missing feature added by the extension.

16
00:01:03,706 --> 00:01:07,641
We select two real listings and open the new keyboard-accessible comparison.

17
00:01:07,641 --> 00:01:12,093
The original website remains intact; OpenPatch adds a personal usability layer on top.

18
00:01:12,093 --> 00:01:16,459
Next we filter for wheelchair access, Urdu, and providers accepting new patients.

19
00:01:16,459 --> 00:01:18,507
Twelve cards become one useful result.

20
00:01:18,507 --> 00:01:24,490
The filtering happens locally in the browser, so private preferences are not sent to MetroCare or to OpenPatch.

21
00:01:24,490 --> 00:01:25,637
We reload the website.

22
00:01:25,637 --> 00:01:30,644
The installed repair runs again automatically, and the unfinished filter choices are still here.

23
00:01:30,644 --> 00:01:35,703
This proves that the result is a working browser feature, not a screenshot or a one-time preview.

24
00:01:35,703 --> 00:01:42,857
Opening the extension again shows that the repair is active only on this website, every operation is healthy, and the permissions are reviewable.

25
00:01:42,857 --> 00:01:45,126
The user can disable or remove it at any time.

26
00:01:45,126 --> 00:01:48,833
Codex is needed only when someone authors and tests a new repair.

27
00:01:48,833 --> 00:01:54,763
Everyone downstream simply installs the verified community patch with no AI, no account, and no API key.

28
00:01:54,763 --> 00:01:58,128
That is OpenPatch: fix the web you have, and share the fix.
